TRIAL AND ERROR — Garden Progress Widget
Back in BeesKnees / src/App.jsx
=========================================


1. THE PROBLEM
--------------
We wanted a "weekly garden" widget on the Home screen that fills in progressively
as mom completes her PT exercises throughout the week. The goal: each set logged
colors in one more region of a garden scene, so by the end of the week the whole
picture is fully colored — a satisfying visual reward.

Constraints:
- Mobile-first (max 430px wide)
- 24 discrete color regions (one unlocks per set batch)
- Rewarding fill order: backgrounds first, characters come to life last
- 0.6s ease-in fade when a region unlocks
- Debug mode to inspect each region in isolation
- Colors fill WITHIN outlines, not on top of them (like a coloring book)


2. HOW WE TRIED TO SOLVE IT
-----------------------------

ATTEMPT 1 — PNG base image + SVG color overlay (mix-blend-mode: multiply)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Approach:
  - Used a coloring-book PNG (public/garden.png) as the base layer
  - Placed an SVG on top with position:absolute, mix-blend-mode:multiply
  - SVG shapes (rectangles, ellipses, circles) approximated where each element
    was in the PNG — e.g. a big rect for the sky, circles for Kavita's face
  - When a group "filled", the shape went from opacity 0 to visible, tinting
    the white area of the PNG with the color

Why it failed:
  - The SVG shapes couldn't precisely follow the PNG outlines — they were blobs
    approximating regions, not actual fills within the drawn lines
  - mix-blend-mode: multiply tints the whole area including slightly outside
    the outlines, so colors "bled" past the black lines
  - The debug bounding-box approach (red dashed rect per group) confirmed the
    shapes were nowhere near the actual drawn content in the PNG
  - Result looked like colored overlays on top of a coloring book, NOT like
    the coloring book was actually being colored in

User feedback:
  "Can we color each item individually instead of panels? Similar to how this
  image is colored?" [showed a reference gnome image with clean flat fills]


ATTEMPT 2 — Pure SVG scene, no PNG (CURRENT)
---------------------------------------------
Approach:
  - Dropped the PNG entirely
  - Rebuilt the entire garden scene as hand-coded SVG primitives
    (rect, circle, ellipse, path, line) inside a single <svg viewBox="0 0 504 360">
  - Each shape has:
      stroke="#2C1810" strokeWidth={2-2.5}   — always-visible dark outline
      style={{ fill: filled(n) ? color : 'white',
               transition: 'fill 0.6s ease-in' }}
  - Colors fill EXACTLY within their own outlines because the fill IS the shape
  - No blend mode needed — this is just normal SVG rendering
  - Debug mode: when active, only the selected group shows as filled (all others
    stay white), so you can visually verify each group in isolation
  - Z-order managed manually: arms drawn before shirts so shirts overlap them
    correctly; hair drawn before face circles so faces sit on top of hair

